1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,960
 - So we've talked about how we reduce replication

2
00:00:02,960 --> 00:00:06,600
 by moving data from sort of one table with too many columns

3
00:00:06,600 --> 00:00:08,480
 into multiple tables and then make links

4
00:00:08,480 --> 00:00:11,160
 with primary keys and foreign keys.

5
00:00:11,160 --> 00:00:13,040
 But we're really not gonna operate at that level

6
00:00:13,040 --> 00:00:14,400
 'cause this is a Django class

7
00:00:14,400 --> 00:00:16,320
 and we're gonna do this in Django.

8
00:00:16,320 --> 00:00:20,400
 And so we use data models in models.py to do this.

9
00:00:20,400 --> 00:00:24,160
 And so a lot of the model field types are characters

10
00:00:24,160 --> 00:00:28,240
 or numbers or dates or long text fields, et cetera.

11
00:00:28,240 --> 00:00:32,200
 But some of them are special and used in this one-to-many

12
00:00:32,200 --> 00:00:34,400
 foreign key, many-to-many fields.

13
00:00:34,400 --> 00:00:37,240
 These are the fields that we use to do the linking

14
00:00:37,240 --> 00:00:38,680
 in our Django data model.

15
00:00:38,680 --> 00:00:41,440
 And so we'll take a look at how these all work.

16
00:00:41,440 --> 00:00:45,160
 So if we have our book instance that links to our book table

17
00:00:45,160 --> 00:00:47,880
 and then our book table that links to the language table,

18
00:00:47,880 --> 00:00:52,200
 we end up with special little lines in our models.

19
00:00:52,200 --> 00:00:54,520
 So most of this is pretty familiar.

20
00:00:54,520 --> 00:00:56,680
 We got a language, it's got a name.

21
00:00:56,680 --> 00:00:59,520
 Now, one thing about Django is it automatically adds

22
00:00:59,520 --> 00:01:01,520
 the ID field and that's kinda nice.

23
00:01:01,520 --> 00:01:05,800
 So you just assume that everything inside of a data model,

24
00:01:05,800 --> 00:01:10,040
 every one of these three tables are going to have ID fields.

25
00:01:10,040 --> 00:01:13,360
 And we don't even talk about the name of the foreign keys

26
00:01:13,360 --> 00:01:15,840
 even though Django names them the way I just showed you

27
00:01:15,840 --> 00:01:18,360
 with the lang_id.

28
00:01:18,360 --> 00:01:19,640
 We have just a regular old thing.

29
00:01:19,640 --> 00:01:23,240
 So lang is suitable as a destination for a link

30
00:01:23,240 --> 00:01:25,520
 'cause it has an ID column automatically added

31
00:01:25,520 --> 00:01:27,160
 by Django every time.

32
00:01:27,160 --> 00:01:29,040
 The book table has an ID column,

33
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:31,280
 so it's suitable for the destination of a link.

34
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:33,200
 But then title and ISBN are there.

35
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:35,880
 And then there's this language and that's the first one.

36
00:01:35,880 --> 00:01:37,920
 And so this is where we're actually modeling

37
00:01:37,920 --> 00:01:40,720
 the need to have links between the book table

38
00:01:40,720 --> 00:01:41,640
 and the language table.

39
00:01:41,640 --> 00:01:46,440
 So we're starting at the from or the start of the arrow

40
00:01:46,440 --> 00:01:50,000
 and we're saying there is, we need to have a language.

41
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:53,520
 But the language is not a string, it's not a number,

42
00:01:53,520 --> 00:01:55,560
 it is a foreign key.

43
00:01:55,560 --> 00:01:58,400
 And it's a foreign key into the table called lang

44
00:01:58,400 --> 00:02:02,280
 and this table called lang matches that table.

45
00:02:02,280 --> 00:02:05,480
 And then we have a couple things.

46
00:02:05,480 --> 00:02:07,000
 I'll talk about on delete in a second

47
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:09,840
 and then null equals true is whether or not it's required.

48
00:02:09,840 --> 00:02:11,480
 And so what it's saying when null is true

49
00:02:11,480 --> 00:02:13,320
 is we're allowing emptiness.

50
00:02:13,320 --> 00:02:17,200
 So that means it's possible to have a record

51
00:02:17,200 --> 00:02:20,720
 in the book table that doesn't have a language.

52
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:24,320
 And so that's what we're saying when we're saying null equals true.

53
00:02:24,320 --> 00:02:28,400
 The instance table points to a book.

54
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:32,960
 It's a foreign key to the book model and it has a do back.

55
00:02:32,960 --> 00:02:37,400
 Now the status was in there and so I sort of shortened it a little bit.

56
00:02:37,400 --> 00:02:40,120
 But we have a foreign key that points into it.

57
00:02:40,120 --> 00:02:44,160
 And so again, we're defining where we have the beginnings of the arrows

58
00:02:44,160 --> 00:02:47,080
 because the ends of the arrows is kind of implicit.

59
00:02:47,080 --> 00:02:52,360
 Django gives us sort of the primary keys for each row in these models

60
00:02:52,360 --> 00:02:54,840
 automatically without us having to say it.

61
00:02:54,840 --> 00:02:58,720
 But you can put it in a Django model if you wanna overwrite the name of it.

62
00:02:58,720 --> 00:03:02,440
 But if you just want a column called id, which everybody pretty much does,

63
00:03:02,440 --> 00:03:07,480
 you just leave it out and Django puts it in for you automatically, okay?

64
00:03:07,480 --> 00:03:11,280
 And so again, you see this from the point of view of the data model

65
00:03:11,280 --> 00:03:16,440
 where we have the arrow between book and language that's a many to one.

66
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:20,200
 And then a book instance to the book is a many to one as well.

67
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:25,560
 And so those foreign key links represent the arrows in this data model.

68
00:03:25,560 --> 00:03:32,560
 Now just to sort of review, you might have done already some of these migrations.

69
00:03:32,560 --> 00:03:36,120
 So once you edit these data models and you get them right,

70
00:03:36,120 --> 00:03:39,440
 you have to do a two step process to get them so

71
00:03:39,440 --> 00:03:42,400
 that your database reflects these models.

72
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:45,280
 The first one is you have to make migrations.

73
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:49,000
 And so the way the make migrations works is it looks through all of

74
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:52,360
 the applications that are registered in your settings.py.

75
00:03:52,360 --> 00:03:56,920
 And for every one, it checks to see if the data model has changed since

76
00:03:56,920 --> 00:03:58,920
 the last run of make migrations.

77
00:03:58,920 --> 00:04:04,200
 So make migrations actually creates files in your application

78
00:04:04,200 --> 00:04:06,400
 based on the models.py.

79
00:04:06,400 --> 00:04:10,600
 And it's a series of files, like 001 here, that's the first one.

80
00:04:10,600 --> 00:04:13,240
 There might, if we changed it and then run make migrations again,

81
00:04:13,240 --> 00:04:18,960
 there'd be an 002, and what it would do is the 002 is evolution beyond the 001.

82
00:04:18,960 --> 00:04:23,440
 Now the migrations are portable, okay, in that they don't,

83
00:04:23,440 --> 00:04:28,320
 they're not specific to the MySQL database, the SQLite database, etc.

84
00:04:28,320 --> 00:04:31,960
 Now the migrate reads those migrations and

85
00:04:31,960 --> 00:04:34,720
 then updates the actual tables in the database.

86
00:04:34,720 --> 00:04:39,080
 And so the migrate is mapping the portable representation of what's supposed

87
00:04:39,080 --> 00:04:43,480
 to be in the database into the actual physical representation in the database.

88
00:04:43,480 --> 00:04:46,880
 Now you'll notice if you run these both twice, once they work,

89
00:04:46,880 --> 00:04:48,400
 they'll say no changes detected.

90
00:04:48,400 --> 00:04:54,000
 Because in the case of the make migrations, it looks at your models and

91
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:58,240
 then looks at what's in the migrations already and says, it's a perfect match.

92
00:04:58,240 --> 00:05:01,040
 And then in the migrate, it looks at what's in the migrations and

93
00:05:01,040 --> 00:05:05,480
 what's in the database table and says, everything's there, everything's been done.

94
00:05:05,480 --> 00:05:10,120
 So this can be confusing because in my documentation,

95
00:05:10,120 --> 00:05:13,200
 I'll say run a make migrations and you say no changes detected.

96
00:05:13,200 --> 00:05:17,000
 Now there's another reason why you might get no changes detected and

97
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:24,440
 that is that you have to add it to the settings.py file before it's gonna be detected.

98
00:05:24,440 --> 00:05:27,800
 So you might have edited a model.py file and changed it.

99
00:05:27,800 --> 00:05:33,320
 But if the application is not in the settings.py, then it won't be detected.

100
00:05:33,320 --> 00:05:37,840
 So the make migrations is reading through all the applications listed in

101
00:05:37,840 --> 00:05:43,360
 the settings.py, checking for differences, deviations between models.py and

102
00:05:43,360 --> 00:05:44,560
 the migrations.

103
00:05:44,560 --> 00:05:47,760
 It might be a little easier just to show you these things.

104
00:05:47,760 --> 00:05:50,520
 Well, that's coming up, I'll show you those in a second.

105
00:05:50,520 --> 00:05:57,160
 If we look at what the migrate does, the migrate creates the SQLite file.

106
00:05:57,160 --> 00:05:59,400
 And so we can take a look at this file.

107
00:05:59,400 --> 00:06:04,920
 You don't have to, but you can take a look at this file after you've run the migrate.

108
00:06:04,920 --> 00:06:10,080
 And you see, so I have a tables, book one percent.

109
00:06:10,080 --> 00:06:12,740
 That's actually a wild card because the like statement,

110
00:06:12,740 --> 00:06:14,920
 that's like the like statement in SQL.

111
00:06:14,920 --> 00:06:18,160
 So that says, show me all the tables that start with book one.

112
00:06:18,160 --> 00:06:19,880
 And you see that there's three of them.

113
00:06:19,880 --> 00:06:22,360
 Book one underscore book, book one underscore instance, and

114
00:06:22,360 --> 00:06:23,920
 book one underscore lang.

115
00:06:23,920 --> 00:06:27,600
 Book one is the application because Django has project and

116
00:06:27,600 --> 00:06:29,000
 then applications within project.

117
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:31,960
 And book one is the application that we're doing.

118
00:06:31,960 --> 00:06:37,200
 And then instance book and lang are the three models that we've specified

119
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:40,520
 in our database, in our models.py.

120
00:06:40,520 --> 00:06:43,400
 So if we take a look using the schema command of book one,

121
00:06:43,400 --> 00:06:48,160
 we can see how the migrate statement produced the table.

122
00:06:48,160 --> 00:06:51,040
 And so we created a book one dot underscore book.

123
00:06:51,040 --> 00:06:54,920
 It has ID, auto increment, all that stuff from the SQL stuff.

124
00:06:54,920 --> 00:07:00,280
 It's got a title, it's got ISPN, and then it's got this lang ID.

125
00:07:00,280 --> 00:07:01,360
 That's the foreign key.

126
00:07:01,360 --> 00:07:04,480
 So it's actually building the foreign key the right way.

127
00:07:04,480 --> 00:07:07,060
 Now in SQLite, there's one way of building foreign keys.

128
00:07:07,060 --> 00:07:09,960
 In MySQL, there's a different way of building foreign keys.

129
00:07:09,960 --> 00:07:14,400
 And so that's all something that the migrate operation understands

130
00:07:14,400 --> 00:07:15,840
 how to build.

131
00:07:15,840 --> 00:07:17,080
 And if you look at the language,

132
00:07:17,080 --> 00:07:19,880
 you just see that there's an ID column that's automatically produced and

133
00:07:19,880 --> 00:07:20,480
 then a name.

134
00:07:20,480 --> 00:07:22,600
 And then if you look at the instance, you see an ID and

135
00:07:22,600 --> 00:07:25,120
 a dude back, which is date.

136
00:07:25,120 --> 00:07:30,600
 And then you see the book ID, which is the foreign key into the book table.

137
00:07:30,600 --> 00:07:35,560
 And so you can kinda see how these tables implement the links as described

138
00:07:35,560 --> 00:07:36,280
 in the picture.

139
00:07:36,280 --> 00:07:41,440
 Now, I was telling you about this on delete.

140
00:07:41,440 --> 00:07:47,520
 So the problem is, is what happens when you have a row in one table,

141
00:07:47,520 --> 00:07:51,160
 like in the book table, that's pointing to a row in a language table, and

142
00:07:51,160 --> 00:07:52,600
 you got records that are pointing there.

143
00:07:52,600 --> 00:07:56,000
 So you've got two books that are pointing to English in this situation.

144
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:58,200
 And then you delete the English row.

145
00:07:58,200 --> 00:08:00,440
 What happens to the rows?

146
00:08:00,440 --> 00:08:02,880
 And you've got, there's a couple of different things that you can do, but

147
00:08:02,880 --> 00:08:05,720
 the two common things are, is cascade.

148
00:08:05,720 --> 00:08:09,960
 And what cascade says is that you're going to delete all the rows.

149
00:08:09,960 --> 00:08:11,040
 If you delete those rows,

150
00:08:11,040 --> 00:08:14,800
 you're gonna delete all the rows that have the matching language ID.

151
00:08:14,800 --> 00:08:19,360
 And set null basically instead says, that's okay.

152
00:08:19,360 --> 00:08:21,880
 We're just gonna wipe out these and make them null.

153
00:08:21,880 --> 00:08:24,320
 And in this English, I mean in this language,

154
00:08:24,320 --> 00:08:27,040
 if we delete a language from the language table,

155
00:08:27,040 --> 00:08:30,240
 we probably just wanna set it to be null, okay?

156
00:08:30,240 --> 00:08:37,480
 And so if you look, you'll see that the relationship between the book and

157
00:08:37,480 --> 00:08:40,880
 the language, which is right here, if we delete one of these things,

158
00:08:40,880 --> 00:08:42,240
 we set it to null.

159
00:08:42,240 --> 00:08:44,120
 We set the corresponding language to null.

160
00:08:44,120 --> 00:08:46,360
 We just throw away these links in a sense.

161
00:08:46,360 --> 00:08:50,040
 And that's okay, cuz books are allowed to not have languages, okay?

162
00:08:50,040 --> 00:08:53,160
 And so languages are allowed to be null, null equals true.

163
00:08:53,160 --> 00:08:54,960
 Languages are allowed to be null.

164
00:08:54,960 --> 00:08:59,400
 But if on the other hand we get rid of a book from our books table,

165
00:08:59,400 --> 00:09:03,960
 then we probably wanna wipe out all of the instances that are related to that book.

166
00:09:03,960 --> 00:09:09,480
 And so that's why we in here say on delete cascade in the book foreign key entry.

167
00:09:09,480 --> 00:09:11,240
 And we don't say null equals true.

168
00:09:11,240 --> 00:09:14,960
 And so set null requires you to be able to say null equals true.

169
00:09:14,960 --> 00:09:19,560
 So you have to say I am willing to allow nulls in this column.

170
00:09:19,560 --> 00:09:23,640
 And by the way, if the thing that this column points to is deleted,

171
00:09:23,640 --> 00:09:26,640
 then set it to null, which means don't delete the row.

172
00:09:26,640 --> 00:09:31,400
 Cascade means if the thing we're pointing to is deleted, then delete this row,

173
00:09:31,400 --> 00:09:33,520
 cuz we don't want inconsistent data.

174
00:09:33,520 --> 00:09:37,240
 We don't want those little things pointing off to absolutely nowhere and

175
00:09:37,240 --> 00:09:38,920
 making absolutely no sense.

176
00:09:38,920 --> 00:09:43,600
 So next I wanna go into a little more detail on models, migrations, and

177
00:09:43,600 --> 00:09:45,920
 databases and how they work at a bit of a low level.

178
00:09:45,920 --> 00:09:55,920
 [MUSIC]

